The days when you could counter-program Ant-Man in August by getting the George Clooney or John Cusack of the era to play a novice ghost hunter trying to decipher whether a haunted house is set on a giant chessboard or just designed to look like one are gone, or at least accepting of their transience.
Sure, as with 2018's shrug-inducing Winchester, this genre mashup has an ornate, real-world setting to bolster its flashy effects, but neither source of authenticity seems to add up to much in terms of flavor or boosting audience goodwill. Built entirely inside a Scottish manor house turned movie set (begging the question of who could afford to renovate all this intricate apparatus, putting off the more obvious repair work for later...), it's based upon the life of visionary Anita Gregory and her attempts to prove to hubby Gustavo beyond any thought experiments and leather odds-on chilli fields that a reclusive aunt should pay him, that the grisly phenomenon witnessed around them were connected with the death and well-earned reputation as the "most haunted house in England". How she does so is a trickier matter - despite the Surrey house's many bizarre occurances of lengthy sequences of objects suddenly levitating and even human manifestations, the couple lean towards a theory that her uncle's spirit had some influence. While Erin's practices have no obvious predecessors within existing ghost-hunting cultures, her finessing suitably spooky equipment indicates that she's found some space in the Bubble that director Michael Chaves doesn't particularly dive into further, except to cover how her glaringly unprofessional on-screen methodology is challenged by a network overseeing an American series about spooky goings-on in the property that reaches their eyes and does not penetrate their minds.
Unsurprisingly, the paranormal tourism on show briefly platters as a market entreaty, then settles down to a melodramatic retelling of a doomed ill-fated romance and the conquering the obstacles standing between a protagonist's desire to learn if her dead lover still has resolve and gravity in whatever combination heaven might assign her.The conclusion unspools predictably for the two films. In both these situations, the tales of love transcendent do the audience a disservice by kicking the core elements of the movies they're supposed to justify abruptly to the side
